{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504399"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2327"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2327"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.28,0.45,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"6034"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45876"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents with acute pain in her wrist after falling onto her right hand. On examination there is tenderness over the wrist, but no apparent deformity and no swelling. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After adequate pain relief, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Open reduction, internal fixation","Application of a molded below elbow cast","Anatomical reduction and plaster backslab","Wrist splint","Broad arm sling"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has fallen on her outstretched hand causing a Colles fracture which is shown on the X-ray. It appears minimally displaced hence it does not require any reduction. Immobilisation of the fracture is necessary for it to heal.\u0026nbsp;This can be achieved by application of a \u003Cstrong\u003Emolded below elbow cast\u003C/strong\u003E for 5 to 6 weeks. This conservative approach is less invasive, avoids the risks associated with surgery. If the fracture were displaced or caused any neurovascular changes, then surgical intervention would be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOften when a fracture is very displaced or there is a plan for surgical fixation in the not too distant future, then a backslab is used. In this case where the fracture is essentially undisplaced then immediate application of a moulded full cast is appropriate. Sometimes the patient would be monitored in hospital overnight for swelling to ensure the cast does not need to be split.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApplication of a backslab would not be unreasonable, but would necessitate definitive management at a later date, be that surgery which this fracture does not need, or application of a molded cast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst application of a molded cast has been the mainstay approach to the management of non or minimally displaced distal radial fractures, the options remain controversial in terms of gold standard care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A Colles fracture with minimal displacement can be managed with a molded below elbow cast."],"references":["Habeebullah A, Vasiljevic A, Abdulla M. Evidence-based review of Colles\u2019 fracture. Trauma. 2015;17(3):191-200. doi:10.1177/1460408614561174","Meena S, Sharma P, Sambharia AK, Dawar A. Fractures of distal radius: an overview. J Family Med Prim Care. 2014;3(4):325-332. doi:10.4103/2249-4863.148101","Mauck BM, Swigler CW. Evidence-Based Review of Distal Radius Fractures. Orthop Clin North Am . 2018; 49:211-22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2327"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17515"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17515"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e1fa00f4-e13a-4ebf-a7c8-7732fd75febe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e1fa00f4-e13a-4ebf-a7c8-7732fd75febe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-06-29T17:05:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T15:01:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2327"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37394"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoj